Poisson Regression Examples from Statistical Rethinking

Oceanic Tool Complexity Dataset

The goal is to model the total number of tools in a society, total_tools, in terms of population and the extent of contact with other islands, contact.

First Model

The first model is as follows: \[ \begin{align*} T_i &\sim \text{Poisson}(\lambda_i)\\ \log \lambda_i &= \alpha_{\text{CID}[i]} + \beta_{\text{CID}[i]} \log P_i\\ \alpha_j &\sim \text{to be specified}\\ \beta_j &\sim \text{to be specified} \end{align*} \] where \(T_i\) is total_tools, \(P_i\) is population and \(\text{CID}[i]\) is a categorical variable that indicates the value of contact for society \(i\). In other words, this is a model in which \(\alpha\) and \(\beta\) vary with contact. Equivalently, the model includes a full set of dummy variables that encode contact along with interactions between these dummies and the log of population. Notice that population is modeled on the log scale. This is discussed further below when an explicit structural model replaces the log-linear predictor used here.

Now letâs consider priors for the \(\alpha_j\) and \(\beta_j\) parameters. To make these easier to think about, it helps to write the model in terms of the centered and standardized value of \(\log P_i\) rather than the raw value:

dat <- dat |> 
  mutate(cid = if_else(contact == 'low', 1, 2),
         lpop = log(population), 
         lpopz = (lpop - mean(lpop)) / sd(lpop)) |> 
  select(total_tools, cid, lpopz)

A value of zero for lpopz indicates that a given society has a log population equal to the sample mean. This helps us think about a reasonable prior for \(\alpha_j\)

A Prior for \(\alpha\)

Ignore cid for the moment, and consider a society with log population equal to the sample mean. If we place a normal prior on \(\alpha\), the model becomes \[ \begin{align*} T_i &\sim \text{Poisson}(\lambda_i)\\ \log \lambda_i &\sim \alpha \\ \alpha &\sim \text{Normal}(\mu, \sigma). \end{align*} \]

So what would be reasonable choices for \(\mu\) and \(\sigma\)? The key point is that \(\alpha\) controls the expected number of tools for a society. (Again, weâre ignoring contact and considering the average society in terms of log population.) Under the model, the expected value of \(T_i\) is \(\lambda_i = e^\alpha\). And since \(\alpha\) is normally distributed, \(\lambda_i\) is lognormal with median \(e^\mu\) and mean \(\exp(\mu + \sigma^2 / 2)\). A âvagueâ prior might set \(\mu = 0\) and \(\sigma = 10\). But this is totally crazy in the present example: the implied lognormal distribution for \(\lambda_i\) would have median \(e^0 = 1\) and mean \(\exp(50)\). Even if we know little or nothing about oceanic societies, weâd be pretty confident that they should have at least a handful of tools, and that theyâre unlikely to more than a hundred tools. The book suggests setting \(\mu = 3\) and \(\sigma = 0.5\), so that \(\lambda_i\) has an a priori median of \(\exp(3) \approx 20\) and mean of \(\exp(3 + 0.5^2/2) \approx 23\).

tibble(x = seq(from = 0.5, to = 100, by = 0.01),
       prior_Crazy = dlnorm(x, 0, 10),
       prior_Reasonable = dlnorm(x, 3, 0.5)) |> 
  pivot_longer(starts_with('prior'), names_prefix = 'prior_', 
               names_to = 'prior', values_to = 'density') |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = x, y = density, col = prior)) +
  geom_line() +
  theme_bw() + 
  xlab('mean number of tools')

A Prior for \(\beta\)

Again, ignore for a moment the variable contact. Given our normalization, the coefficient \(\beta\) gives the effect of a one standard deviation change in log population on \(\log \lambda_i\). Suppose we choose to put a normal prior on \(\beta\). Again we might be tempted to use a vague prior, e.g.Â \(\text{Normal}(\mu = 0, \sigma = 10)\). But this implies totally crazy marginal effects a priori. The easiest way to see this is by simulation. Weâll stick with the \(\text{Normal}(\mu = 3, \sigma = 0.5)\) prior for \(\alpha\) and try the âvagueâ prior for \(\beta\):

set.seed(10)
n <- 100
tibble(i = 1:n, 
       a = rnorm(n, 3, 0.5),
       b = rnorm(n, 0, 10)) |> 
  expand_grid(x = seq(-2, 2, length.out = 100)) |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = x, y = exp(a + b * x), group = i)) +
  geom_line() +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 1000)) +
  ylab('total tools') + 
  xlab('z-score of log population') +
  theme_bw()

Itâs wildly implausible that a tenth of a standard deviation change in log population should take total tools from close to zero to over a thousand. A more reasonable prior for \(\beta\) would be something like \(\text{Normal}(\mu = 0, \sigma = 0.2)\), which gives a much more reasonable picture: note the different y-axis

set.seed(10)
n <- 100
tibble(i = 1:n, 
       a = rnorm(n, 3, 0.5),
       b = rnorm(n, 0, 0.2)) |> 
  expand_grid(x = seq(-2, 2, length.out = 100)) |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = x, y = exp(a + b * x), group = i)) +
  geom_line() +
  ylab('total tools') + 
  xlab('z-score of log population') +
  theme_bw()

Simulating from the Posterior

Based on the experiments from above, weâll use the following priors: \[ \begin{align*} \alpha_j &\sim \text{Normal}(3, 0.5)\\ \beta_j & \sim \text{Normal}(0, 0.2) \end{align*} \]

    total_tools ~ dpois(lambda),

    a[cid] ~ dnorm(3, 0.5),
    b[cid] ~ dnorm(0, 0.2)
  ), data = dat, chains = 4, cmdstan = TRUE # faster!
)

We can also look at some diagnostics:

We see that the model seems to be mixing well. Hereâs the underlying STAN code used to fit the model:

stancode(m11_10)
data{
    array[10] int total_tools;
     vector[10] lpopz;
    array[10] int cid;
}
parameters{
     vector[2] a;
     vector[2] b;
}
model{
     vector[10] lambda;
    b ~ normal( 0 , 0.2 );
    a ~ normal( 3 , 0.5 );
    for ( i in 1:10 ) {
        lambda[i] = a[cid[i]] + b[cid[i]] * lpopz[i];
        lambda[i] = exp(lambda[i]);
    }
    total_tools ~ poisson( lambda );
}

A Structural Model

This is fun. Rather than simply using a log link function and a linear predictor on the log scale we can actually try to think about a production technology for tools! Hereâs a simple model in discrete time suggested in the book. Suppose that the change in the average number of tools from one period to the next is given by \[ \Delta T = \alpha P^\beta - \gamma T. \] The parameter \(\gamma\) represents depreciation: from one period to the next, a fraction \(\gamma\) of existing tools falls out of use and disappears. The parameters \(\alpha\) and \(\beta\) govern the creation of new tools. The rate at which new tools are developed depends on population size according to a Cobb-Douglas model. We would expect diminishing returns to population: \(\beta < 1\). Notice that this model is on the scale of population rather than the logarithm of population. Notice further that this is a model in which population is exogenous. We could think of more complicated models, but this is a very small and limited dataset. In equilibrium \(\Delta T = 0\), i.e.Â \(\alpha P^\beta = \gamma T\). Solving for the equilibrium number of tools \(T^*\) gives \[ T^* = \frac{\alpha}{\gamma} P^\beta. \] This is a structural model. To turn it into a statistical model, we need a likelihood i.e.Â a distribution for noise around \(T^*\). Since total_tools is a count variable with no upper bound, the maximum entropy distribution is a Poisson. So we specify the model as follows \[ \begin{align*} T_i &\sim \text{Poisson}(\lambda_i) \\ \lambda_i &= \alpha_{\text{CID}[i]} P^{\beta_{\text{CID}[i]}}/\gamma. \end{align*} \] This allows the production technology for new tools, characterized by \(\alpha\) and \(\beta\), to vary depending on the extent of contact that the society had with other societies. The book doesnât mention this, but it seems that \(\gamma\) shouldnât be separately identifiable. If Iâm right about this, the posterior for this parameter should equal the prior. Weâll take a look below. All of the parameters should be positive. The book places lognormal priors on \(\alpha_{\text{CID}[i]}\) and standard exponential priors on \(\beta_{\text{CID}[i]}\) and \(\gamma\).

data(Kline)
dat2 <- as_tibble(Kline) 
rm(Kline)
dat2 <- dat2 |> 
  mutate(cid = if_else(contact == 'low', 1, 2)) |> 
  select(population, cid, total_tools)

m11_11 <- ulam(
  alist(
    total_tools ~ dpois(lambda),
    lambda <- exp(a[cid]) * population^b[cid] / g,
    # Not sure why the book uses a normal and then exponentiates rather
    # than just using a lognormal. Maybe to avoid numerical issues?
    a[cid] ~ dnorm(1, 1),
    b[cid] ~ dexp(1),
    g ~ dexp(1)
  ), data = dat2, chains = 4, cmdstan = TRUE # faster!
)

I think those warnings are OK: occasionally thereâs a numerical issue when working with constrained parameters. But as long as it happens only occasionally, it should be fine. The STAN code for this model is very easy to understand:

stancode(m11_11)
data{
    array[10] int total_tools;
    array[10] int population;
    array[10] int cid;
}
parameters{
     vector[2] a;
     vector<lower=0>[2] b;
     real<lower=0> g;
}
model{
     vector[10] lambda;
    g ~ exponential( 1 );
    b ~ exponential( 1 );
    a ~ normal( 1 , 1 );
    for ( i in 1:10 ) {
        lambda[i] = exp(a[cid[i]]) * population[i]^b[cid[i]]/g;
    }
    total_tools ~ poisson( lambda );
}

It looks like the posterior doesnât quite match the prior, but this might just be sampling error. I still donât see how this parameter is identified in the frequentist sense. Presumably normalizing it to one shouldnât have an effect on the results except insofar as it changes the interpretation of the \(e^{\alpha_j}\) parameters.

Comparing the Statistical and Structural Models

Now weâd like to see how the purely âstatisticalâ Poisson regression model compares to the âstructuralâ model. We canât compare the parameters directly, since they have different meanings. But both models specify \(y_i \sim \text{Poisson}(\lambda_i)\); they simply parameterize \(\lambda_i\) differently. Itâs actually a bit more helpful to think about this in terms of a function \(\lambda(\text{Covariates}_i)\), since then we can imagine evaluating \(\lambda_i\) for a value of \(\text{Covariates}_i\) that doesnât necessarily appear in our dataset. We can posterior draws for the model parameters to approximate the implied posterior for \(\lambda(\cdot)\) evaluated wherever we like. Itâs fairly straightforward to do this âby handâ using extract.samples(). But thereâs a faster and simpler way in this case, using the link() function from rethinking. Itâs behavior is very similar to that of the base R function predict() except that it defaults to producing predictions on the scale of the outcome rather than the scale of the linear predictor, and it produces posterior samples rather than a prediction. If you want a prediction, then simply process the draws however you like, e.g.Â taking the mean to obtain the optimal prediction under squared error loss.

Weâll start with the âstatisticalâ model and make predictions over a sequence of values of lpopz with cid set to 1. In other words, weâll make predictions for âlow contactâ societies:

lpopz_seq <- seq(-5, 2.4, length.out = 100)
lambda <- link(m11_10, data = data.frame(lpopz = lpopz_seq, cid = 1))
str(lambda)
 num [1:2000, 1:100] 4.11 8 5.83 2.99 5.25 ...

notice that the result is a matrix with as many columns as there are values of lpopz in lpopz_seq. Each row is a collection of draws from the posterior at the corresponding value of lpopz. Iâm not entirely sure why it defaults to 2000 posterior draws: this doesnât seem to accord with the documentation, but it does accord with the messages that R prints to the console so itâs definitely correct. Thus, we can plot the posterior mean prediction as follows:

plot(lpopz_seq, colMeans(lambda), type = 'l',
     xlab = 'log population (z-score)', ylab = 'total tools')

Now that we have the idea, letâs make a more useful plot that shows the data, the predicted relationship for both high and low contact societies, and HPDs. Letâs also make the plot on the raw population scale since thatâs easier to understand:

lambda_low <- link(m11_10, data = data.frame(lpopz = lpopz_seq, cid = 1))
lambda_high <- link(m11_10, data = data.frame(lpopz = lpopz_seq, cid = 2))

summarize_predictions <- function(predictions) {
  tibble(mean = colMeans(predictions),
         lower = apply(predictions, 2, quantile, probs = 0.05),
         upper = apply(predictions, 2, quantile, probs = 0.95))
}

data(Kline)
lpop_mean <- mean(log(Kline$population))
lpop_sd <- sd(log(Kline$population))
pop_seq <- exp(lpop_mean + lpop_sd * lpopz_seq)

predictions_low <- summarize_predictions(lambda_low) |> 
  mutate(population = pop_seq, contact = 'low')

predictions_high <- summarize_predictions(lambda_high) |> 
  mutate(population = pop_seq, contact = 'high')

predictions <- bind_rows(predictions_low, predictions_high) 
predictions |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = population, y = mean, col = contact, lty = contact)) +
  geom_line() + 
  geom_point(data = Kline, aes(x = population, y = total_tools)) +
  geom_ribbon(aes(ymin = lower, ymax = upper, fill = contact), alpha = 0.2) +
  ylab('total tools') +
  ggtitle("'Statistical' Model") +
  theme_minimal()

Notice how the mean curves cross at very high populations. This comes entirely from the single observation with high population: Hawaii. But this probably doesnât make sense from a scientific perspective.

In the âstatisticalâ model, the intercept is a free parameter. But we actually know what the intercept should be here: zero people means zero tools. The âstructuralâ model imposes this, so it gives more reasonable extrapolations:

# Remember that this model is on the *raw* population scale!
lambda_low <- link(m11_11, data = data.frame(population = pop_seq, cid = 1))
lambda_high <- link(m11_11, data = data.frame(population = pop_seq, cid = 2))

predictions_low <- summarize_predictions(lambda_low) |> 
  mutate(population = pop_seq, contact = 'low')

predictions_high <- summarize_predictions(lambda_high) |> 
  mutate(population = pop_seq, contact = 'high')

predictions <- bind_rows(predictions_low, predictions_high) 
predictions |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = population, y = mean, col = contact, lty = contact)) +
  geom_line() + 
  geom_point(data = Kline, aes(x = population, y = total_tools)) +
  geom_ribbon(aes(ymin = lower, ymax = upper, fill = contact), alpha = 0.2) +
  ylab('total tools') +
  ggtitle("'Structural' Model") +
  theme_minimal()

Over-dispersion

Iâm not going to go through all of the plots and diagnostics right now because Iâm lazy! But to make a long story short, as weâve already seen Hawaii turns out to be an extremely influential observation in the models from above. It is a low contact society with an extremely high population and large number of tools. Including or excluding Hawaii makes a big difference to the posterior. Why is this so? Both of the Poisson models from above assume that the rate parameter is identical for two societies with the same covariates. In other words, they donât allow for unobserved heterogeneity in the rate parameter. To build this into the model, we can add a multiplicative error term: \[ y_i \sim \text{Poisson}(\lambda_i \nu_i) \] where \(\lambda_i\) is the âsystematicâ part of the model, the part that involves covariates, and \(\nu_i\) is unobserved heterogeneity. In this multiplicative parameterization, it makes sense for \(\nu_i\) to have expected value equal to one. If it is independent of \(\lambda_i\) we obtain a Poisson mixture distribution. This is equivalent to including an additive error term on the log scale. When \(\nu_i\) is assumed to follow a gamma distribution with shape and rate parameters both equal to \(\phi\), we obtain the Gamma-Poisson mixture aka the âNegative Binomialâ model. This model breaks the link between the mean and variance that holds in a simple Poisson model. The new parameter \(\phi\) allows over-dispersion. Confusingly, different sources use different parameterizations. According to the book, the one used in rethinking is such that when \[ y_i \sim \text{Gamma-Poisson}(\lambda_i, \phi) \] the mean of \(y_i\) is \(\lambda_i\) and the variance is \(\lambda_i + \lambda_i^2 / \phi\). So as \(\phi\) tends to infinity, this approaches a standard Poisson regression model. This also accords with the parameterization I was taught! The base R function dgampois(), however, appears to be parameterized in terms of \(1/\phi\), although I need to double-check this.

We can implement this with only minimal changes to our code from above. All we need to do is change the likelihood, and add a prior for the new parameter \(\phi\):

m12_2 <- ulam(
  alist(

Simulation Example with Offsets

We often think of the Poisson parameter \(\lambda_i\) as a rate of events per unit time or per unit space. If the observations \(i\) are recorded over different lengths of time or distance, then we need to account for this in our model. We call these varying lengths of time or distance exposures. The example from the book takes \(Y_i\) to be the number of manuscripts produced by monastery \(i\). If one monastery records the number of manuscripts in a day while another records the number of manuscripts in a week we will need to account for this difference in our model.

If there are \(\lambda\) events per unit time, then in an interval of length \(\tau\) there will be, on average, \(\mu = \lambda \tau\) events. If, as above, we have a linear model on the log scale for \(\lambda_i\), then \[ \log \mu_i = \log (\lambda_i \tau_i) = \log \tau_i + \log \lambda_i = \log \tau_i + \alpha + \beta x_i. \] In other words: to translate from a model for the rate \(\lambda_i\) to a model for the mean number of events \(\mu_i\), on the log scale we merely need to subtract \(\log \tau_i\). The idea here is that \(\tau_i\) is known, as in the monastery example. In effect, we add another predictor to our log-linear model, \(\log \tau_i\), but we know in advance that its coefficient is one. This term is called an offset.

Hereâs a little simulation example. There are two monasteries: the first has a rate of \(\lambda = 1.5\) manuscripts per day and records daily totals; the second has a rate of \(\lambda = 0.5\) manuscripts per day but records weekly totals.

n0 <- 30 # observe daily counts for 30 days 
y0 <- rpois(n0, lambda = 1.5) # rate of 1.5 manuscripts / day 

n1 <- 4 # observe weekly counts for 4 weeks
y1 <- rpois(n1, lambda = 7 * 0.5) # rate of 0.5 manuscripts / day times 7 days

manuscripts <- tibble(y = c(y0, y1),
                      monastery = c(rep(0, n0), rep(1, n1)), # monastery dummy
                      exposure = c(rep(1, n0), rep(7, n1)), # exposure in days
                      log_days = log(exposure))

For this example, the book uses a normal approximation to the posterior rather than running Hamiltonian MC:

m11_12 <- quap(
  alist(
    y ~ dpois(lambda),
    log(lambda) <- log_days + a + b * monastery, 
    a ~ dnorm(0, 1), # not great prior choices, but it won't matter!
    b ~ dnorm(0, 1)
  ), data = manuscripts
)

Now we can compute posterior predictions of the daily rate for each of the two monasteries:

posterior <- extract.samples(m11_12)
lambda0 <- with(posterior, exp(a)) 
lambda1 <- with(posterior, exp(a + b))
precis(tibble(lambda0, lambda1, diff = lambda1 - lambda0))

Zero-inflated Counts

This is a continuation of the monastery example. Sometimes the monks spend the whole day drinking and donât work on any manuscripts. On these days, they produce zero manuscripts. On other days, they work on manuscripts and finish a Poisson distributed number of them where the Poisson rate is \(\lambda\) manuscripts per day. Itâs possible that the monks will finish zero manuscripts even on a day that they spend working rather than drinking. Because there are two ways to obtain zero manuscripts in this model, it wonât match a standard Poisson distribution. Suppose that the monks flip a coin each day to decide whether to drink or work. The probability that they drink is \(p\) and the probability that they work is \((1 - p)\). Then the probability that they produce zero manuscripts on a give day is \[ \begin{align*} \mathbb{P}(Y = 0|p, \lambda) &= \mathbb{P}(Y=0|\text{Drink},p, \lambda) \mathbb{P}(\text{Drink}|p, \lambda) + \mathbb{P}(Y=0|\text{Work},p,\lambda) \mathbb{P}(\text{Work}|p,\lambda)\\ &= 1 \times p + \frac{e^{-\lambda}\lambda^0}{0!}\times (1 - p)\\ &= p + (1 - p) \exp(-\lambda) \end{align*} \] while the probability that they produce \(y > 0\) manuscripts is \[ \begin{align*} \mathbb{P}(Y = y|p, \lambda) &= \mathbb{P}(Y=y|\text{Drink},p, \lambda) \mathbb{P}(\text{Drink}|p, \lambda) + \mathbb{P}(Y = y|\text{Work}, p, \lambda) \mathbb{P}(\text{Work}|p, \lambda)\\ &= 0 \times p + \frac{e^{-\lambda}\lambda^y}{y!} \times (1 - p)\\ &= (1 - p) \frac{\lambda^y \exp(-\lambda)}{y!}. \end{align*} \] The preceding two equations completely describe a probability distribution for \(Y\) that allows excess zeros: the zero-inflated Poisson. Letâs call it \(\text{ZIPoisson}(p, \lambda)\). We can use this distribution to build a regression model in which \(p\) and \(\lambda\) depend on covariates: \[ \begin{align*} Y_i &\sim \text{ZIPoisson}(p_i, \lambda_i)\\ \text{logit}(p_i) &= \alpha_p + \beta_p x_i\\ \log(\lambda_i) &= \alpha_\lambda + \beta_\lambda x_i \end{align*} \] where \(\text{logit}(p_i) \equiv \log[p_i / (1 - p_i)]\). We could easily include more covariates and thereâs no need for the covariates in each equation to be the same: this is merely an example of what is possible.

Now weâll simulate some data from this model. For simplicity, thereâs no regressor here but it would be easy (and a good exercise!) to add one:

p_true <- 0.2 # Monks drink on 20% of days
lambda_true <- 1 # When working, monasteries average 1 manuscript / day

n <- 365 # A year's worth of daily data on manuscript production

set.seed(365) # This is the seed used in the book

drink <- rbinom(n, 1, p_true) # indicator for whether the monks drink
y <- (1 - drink) * rpois(n, lambda_true) # manuscripts produce

Note that we will only âobserveâ y; drink is merely used in the simulation. (If we knew drink we could simply analyze the days when the monks were working as a plain vanilla Poisson regression!) Now we can fit the model:

m12_3 <- ulam(
  alist(
    y ~ dzipois(p, lambda),
    logit(p) <- ap,
    log(lambda) <- al,
    ap ~ dnorm(-1.5, 1),
    al ~ dnorm(1, 0.5)
  ), data = list(y = y), chains = 4, cmdstan = TRUE # faster!
)

These are the priors from the book. Itâs worth taking a look at them before we fit the model. The prior \(\alpha_p \sim \text{Normal}(\mu = -1.5, \sigma = 1)\) is on the log-odds scale. To convert it to a probability, we need to pass it through the inverse of \(\text{logit}\), namely the standard logistic CDF plogis():

n_sims <- 50000
tibble(ap = rnorm(n_sims, -1.5, 1), p = plogis(ap)) |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = p)) +
  geom_density() +
  geom_vline(xintercept = p_true) +
  theme_bw()

This is a prior that âgently nudgesâ the estimated probability of drinking below 0.5. Itâs not a very stark prior, but it encodes the idea that the monks probably donât spend most days drinking. Similarly, we can examine the prior \(\alpha_\lambda \sim \text{Normal}(\mu = 1, \sigma = 0.5)\) for the daily rate of manuscript production conditional on not spending the day drinking

tibble(al = rnorm(n_sims, 1, 0.5), lambda = exp(al)) |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = lambda)) +
  geom_density() +
  geom_vline(xintercept = lambda_true) +
  theme_bw()

This is a prior that is fairly certain that the monks produce fewer than 10 manuscripts per day, on average. Now that weâve looked at the priors, letâs look at a summary of the posterior:

precis(m12_3)

The STAN code for this one is a bit more complicated. There are some details about it on page 379 of the book. In short: dzipois() is a function from the rethinking package that is implemented in a particular way to avoid numerical problems. We can see exactly how this works in the STAN code:

stancode(m12_3)
data{
    array[365] int y;
}
parameters{
     real ap;
     real al;
}
model{
     real p;
     real lambda;
    al ~ normal( 1 , 0.5 );
    ap ~ normal( -1.5 , 1 );
    lambda = al;
    lambda = exp(lambda);
    p = ap;
    p = inv_logit(p);
    for ( i in 1:365 ) {
        if ( y[i]==0 )
            target += log_mix( p , 0 , poisson_lpmf(0|lambda) );
        if ( y[i] > 0 )
            target += log1m( p ) + poisson_lpmf(y[i] | lambda );
    }
}
